In article &lt;1178@csd4.milw.wisc.edu&gt; james@csd4.milw.wisc.edu (Jim Lowe) writes:
&gt;Should each network number have a registered in-addr.arpa record with
&gt;the root servers?  This doesn't seem to be the case. 

  The problem is that applying for a domain name (*.edu, *.com or whatever)
does NOT automatically give you the associated in-addr.arpa domain! You have
to apply for that separately, and many domains don't know this, and so even
if they have the proper PTR records in THEIR name server, the root servers
don't know this so queries get rejected. One possible reason for this apparent
illogic is that many domains (such as ours) have more than one in-addr.arpa
domain (we have 116.128.in-addr.arpa and 117.128.in-addr.arpa), i.e. they
have more than one net in their domain.
  The bottom line is, you have to apply separately for the in-addr.arpa domain,
and not all sites have done this. I was able to add the proper referrals to
the root servers by just sending mail to hostmaster@sri-nic.arpa requesting
them to do so (after I had created the proper SOA and PTR records in my
own server, of course).
   In addition to that, not all sites bother to keep their PTR records up to 
date, either.

--Greg

